# How kube-proxy Routes Traffic

The ClusterIP is a **fiction** — nothing listens on `10.96.42.7`. **kube-proxy** makes it real.

> DaemonSet on every node → watches Services + Endpoints → programs the **kernel** so Service IP → a real Pod IP.

## Three modes

- **iptables** *(default)* — DNAT to a random endpoint. Simple; rules grow with scale.
- **IPVS** — kernel IP Virtual Server; hash lookup, richer algorithms. Faster at scale.
- **nftables** — modern filter framework; the future.

## Day to day

- **Debug** — `iptables -t nat -L -n` on a node.
- **Mesh** — Istio/Linkerd intercept *before* kube-proxy, on top of it.
- **Scale** — past a few thousand Services → IPVS / nftables.

## Kill the misconception

> kube-proxy is **NOT** in the data path. It writes **rules**; packets flow **kernel-direct, Pod→Pod**. Service IPs are free at runtime.
